Certainly! Implementing Exactly-Once Semantics (EOS) in a distributed system ensures that each message is processed exactly once, even in the presence of failures or retries. This is particularly important for applications like order management systems where data integrity and consistency are crucial.

### End-to-End Setup for Exactly-Once Semantics

#### 1. **Kafka Configuration**
Ensure your Kafka cluster supports Exactly-Once Semantics (EOS). This requires Kafka version 0.11 or later, along with the following configurations:

```properties
# Enable transactional support in Kafka brokers
transaction.state.log.replication.factor=3
transaction.state.log.min.isr=2

# Ensure that all replicas have fully replicated a message before considering it committed
acks=all
```

#### 2. **Producer Configuration**
Configure your producers to use transactions and enable idempotence.

```properties
spring.kafka.producer.transaction-id-prefix=my-producer-
spring.kafka.producer.enable-idempotence=true
spring.kafka.producer.properties.max.in.flight=5
spring.kafka.producer.properties.retries=10
```

#### 3. **Consumer Configuration**
Configure your consumers to use exactly-once semantics.

```properties
spring.kafka.consumer.group-id=my-consumer-group
spring.kafka.consumer.enable.auto.commit=false
spring.kafka.consumer.isolation.level=read_committed
```

### Example Producer Implementation

Ensure that the producer uses transactions and commits offsets after processing messages.

#### KafkaProducer with Transactions

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.KafkaProducer;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerRecord;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private KafkaProducer<String, byte[]> kafkaProducer;
    @Autowired
    private SchemaRegistryClient schemaRegistryClient;

    public void createOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        // Business logic for creating an order
        Order order = new Order(request);

        String subject = "order-created-value";
        Schema schema = getSchema(subject);

        byte[] eventBytes = convertToAvro(order, schema);

        try (KafkaProducer<String, byte[]> producer = kafkaProducer) {
            // Start a transaction
            producer.initTransactions();

            if (!producer.beginTransaction().isSuccess()) {
                throw new RuntimeException("Failed to start transaction");
            }

            // Send the message within the transaction
            ProducerRecord<String, byte[]> record = new ProducerRecord<>("order-topic", "ORDER_CREATED", eventBytes);
            producer.send(record);

            // Commit the transaction
            producer.commitTransaction();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Error processing order creation: " + e.getMessage());
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }

    private Schema getSchema(String subject) {
        return new CachedSchemaRegistryClient(schemaRegistryClient).getLatestSchemaMetadata(subject).getSchema();
    }

    private byte[] convertToAvro(Order order, Schema schema) {
        SpecificDatumWriter<GenericRecord> writer = new SpecificDatumWriter<>(schema);
        try (ByteArrayOutputStream out = new ByteArrayOutputStream()) {
            Encoder encoder = EncoderFactory.get().binaryEncoder(out, null);
            writer.write(order.toJson(), encoder);
            encoder.flush();
            return out.toByteArray();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to serialize order event", e);
        }
    }

    private String toJson(Order order) {
        try {
            return new ObjectMapper().writeValueAsString(order);
        } catch (JsonProcessingException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to convert Order to JSON", e);
        }
    }
}
